name: Dusky Purpletuft
rangeDescription: Southeastern venezuela to the guianas and far northern brazil (roraima)
description: Small, uncommon cotinga; usually seen perched in the uppermost bare branches of a high tree. At a distance, appears mostly black with a conspicuous white line down center of breast.

name: White-headed Petrel
rangeDescription: Islands in southern indian ocean and southern pacific ocean
description: A large gadfly petrel with a pale white head and a distinctive dark eye-patch. Back is pale gray with darker outer wings, creating an “M” shape on the back.

name: Magpie Mannikin
rangeDescription: Senegal to kenya, southward to tanzania, zanzibar, zambia, and kwazulu-natal
description: Large waxbill with a big bill. Shows a black head, brown back, and black scallops along the sides of the breast.

name: Xantus's Hummingbird
rangeDescription: Arid scrub of southern baja california
description: Stocky, medium-sized hummingbird of the southern half of Baja California peninsula. No similar species in its limited range; endemic.

name: Moluccan Woodcock
rangeDescription: Northern moluccas (obi and bacan)
description: A chunky, snipe-like forest-dwelling shorebird with cryptic plumage, a stunted tail, and a long powerful bill. Buff below with extensive bold black markings above.

name: Lesser Kestrel
rangeDescription: Mediterranean basin to eastern china; winters to southern asia and southern africa
description: Elegant little falcon, often seen in groups. Males are unspotted above with a blue-gray head and similarly-colored patches on the upperwings; also note largely pale underwings.

name: Jameson's Snipe
rangeDescription: Andes of colombia to western venezuela and eastern bolivia
description: Chunky snipe of very high elevations in the Andes. Plumage has a complicated pattern of brown, buff, and black; note extensive barring on underparts and thick, drooping bill.

name: Mikado Pheasant
rangeDescription: Montane forest of central taiwan
description: A stunning pheasant species endemic to Taiwan, the male a rich slaty blue with white markings and red facial skin, the female rich brown with extensive pale feather edges. Generally retiring, foraging quietly in the undergrowth of montane forests, but occasionally seen in the open, particularly in places where fed.

name: Wallace's Fairywren
rangeDescription: Lowlands of new guinea, including misool (raja ampat islands, off western new guinea), aru islands (off southwestern new guinea), and yapen (cenderawasih bay, off northwestern new guinea)
description: A tiny bird of foothill forest mid-storey and canopy. White underparts, rufous back with two dotted white wing bars, a black cap with white cheek stripe and pale blue flecked crown.

name: Tamaulipas Pygmy-Owl
rangeDescription: Northeastern mexico (southwestern tamaulipas, eastern san luis potosí, and northern hidalgo)
description: Very small owl of tropical forest in the foothills of northeast Mexico where it is endemic. Favors forest canopy and is rarely seen, but sometimes hunts low at edges; active in the daytime.

name: Spix's Woodcreeper
rangeDescription: Southeastern amazonian brazil south of the amazon river
description: Medium-sized woodcreeper with a slightly curved bill. Has buff spots on its head which become elongated semi-circles with dark edges on the mantle and underparts.

name: Salvin's Albatross
rangeDescription: Crozet, snares, and bounty islands
description: Breeds in New Zealand and ranges across temperate South Pacific to Humboldt Current, where it is by far the most numerous “gray-hooded” albatross off Chile and Peru. All ages have gray hood, narrow black leading edge on the underwing (wider and messier on immature).

name: Brasilia Tapaculo
rangeDescription: Southern brazil (southern goiás, distrito federal, and western minas gerais)
description: Small gray bird, typically fiendishly difficult to see in swampy gallery forest with ferns. Plump, with a short tail; note the cinnamon and black bars on vent.

name: Sao Tome Paradise-Flycatcher
rangeDescription: São tomé island (gulf of guinea)
description: A distinctive long-tailed paradise-flycatcher with different-looking sexes. Male is glossy blue-black with a pale blue bill and blue eye-rings; female has a dark crown, a gray face, rusty upperparts, and pale underparts.
imageCreditName: Lars Petersson | My World of Bird Photography

name: Magpie Starling
rangeDescription: Sudan to southern ethiopia, somalia, northeastern uganda, kenya, and tanzania
description: An unusual and distinctive starling of dry country. Males are dark above and white below, with a blue-black hood and upperparts; females are dark gray.

name: Mexican Violetear
rangeDescription: Open mountain slopes of southern mexico to north-central nicaragua
description: Rather large, overall bright green hummingbird of highlands. Favors pine-oak forest and edge, especially overgrown clearings and roadsides with dense flower banks.

name: Copper-tailed Starling
rangeDescription: Sierra leone to ghana
description: A small rainforest starling with a short square tail. In poor light, can look completely black, but usually shows a purple head; the rest of the body and wing are black with blue gloss.

name: Rennell Gerygone
rangeDescription: Rennell (southeastern solomon islands)
description: Small warbler-like bird, endemic to Rennell Island, in the southern Solomon Islands. Fairly distinctive within its tiny range; note the slender black bill, gray cap, white throat, olive back, and yellow belly.

name: Blue-capped Cordonbleu
rangeDescription: Far southeastern south sudan, far southeastern ethiopia, southern somalia, kenya, and tanzania
description: A slim, long-tailed, pretty waxbill. The upperparts are pale brown, the underparts and tail blue, and the bill pink.

name: Laysan Duck
rangeDescription: Laysan island (northwestern hawaiian islands)
description: Highly range-restricted duck with a splotchy white “comma” around each eye. Found only on the Midway Islands, where it is the only resident duck.
